<div id="post-5" class="post-5 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized">
	<div class="post-header">
		<div class="date"><a href="https://prisonscrew.wordpress.com/2011/10/22/statement-of-purpose/">October 22, 2011</a></div>

		
		<h2><a href="https://prisonscrew.wordpress.com/2011/10/22/statement-of-purpose/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Statement of purpose.">Statement of purpose.</a></h2>

		<div class="author">
					</div>


	</div><!--end post header-->
	<div class="entry clear">
				<p>Making money from running a private prison is not difficult. Cut staff, employ low skills people on a low pay contract, tolerate high levels of drugs inside, shift difficult prisoners to the public sector and remove the private prisons from the league tables.</p>
<p> <br />
This has all been done with current private prisons and is a matter of record.<br />
In this series of blogs I will;<br />
Outline the reality of life in prison as the budget cuts continue to bite.<br />
Ask the difficult questions about public money in the crown estate. The figures don&#8217;t add up.<br />
Explore the political motivation to privatise prisons.</p>
<p>Watch the players, tell you who they are and who their friends are. <br />
The first of the blogs will be a lovely teaser. How to manage newly privatised prison drug services, ensuring lots of service users are processed through the program, none continue using drugs and none reoffend thereby allowing the private company to move a large amount of public money into their account. Naturally, no actual drug users will be helped in the course of this program but the detail is gripping.</p>
<p>At no point will I be sharing any information relating to security matters or individuals currently in prison.</p>
<p><strong><em>Rattling the keys for you</em></strong></p>
